</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1683,1996]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">
<emphasis box="[199,326,1685,1708]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Mesosoma.</emphasis>
Pronotum, mesoscutum and mesoscutellum densely and coarsely punctate (
<figureCitation box="[1185,1254,1683,1708]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1647,1670]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 8. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 2. Antenna; 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Head, dorsal view; 5. Head and mesosoma, dorsal view; 6. Head and mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Fore wing; 8. Hind wing. Scale bars = 0.3 mm for 2, 0.4 mm for 3, 0.45 mm for 4, 0.7 mm for 5, 0.9 mm for 6 and 7, and 1.1 mm for 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Tegula mostly smooth and shining, slightly recurved posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[722,791,1719,1744]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1647,1670]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 8. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 2. Antenna; 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Head, dorsal view; 5. Head and mesosoma, dorsal view; 6. Head and mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Fore wing; 8. Hind wing. Scale bars = 0.3 mm for 2, 0.4 mm for 3, 0.45 mm for 4, 0.7 mm for 5, 0.9 mm for 6 and 7, and 1.1 mm for 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Mesonotum without anteromedian lines or longitudinal ridge. Notaulus short, incomplete anteriorly, one quarter of mesoscutum length, (
<figureCitation box="[1051,1119,1755,1780]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1647,1670]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 8. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 2. Antenna; 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Head, dorsal view; 5. Head and mesosoma, dorsal view; 6. Head and mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Fore wing; 8. Hind wing. Scale bars = 0.3 mm for 2, 0.4 mm for 3, 0.45 mm for 4, 0.7 mm for 5, 0.9 mm for 6 and 7, and 1.1 mm for 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Parapsidal line incomplete anteriorly and posteriorly, shorter and shallower than notaulus (
<figureCitation box="[919,995,1791,1816]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1647,1670]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 8. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 2. Antenna; 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Head, dorsal view; 5. Head and mesosoma, dorsal view; 6. Head and mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Fore wing; 8. Hind wing. Scale bars = 0.3 mm for 2, 0.4 mm for 3, 0.45 mm for 4, 0.7 mm for 5, 0.9 mm for 6 and 7, and 1.1 mm for 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Mesoscutellum evenly convex, not projected posterad, with dense whitish setae along lateral margin (
<figureCitation box="[940,1014,1827,1852]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1647,1670]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 8. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 2. Antenna; 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Head, dorsal view; 5. Head and mesosoma, dorsal view; 6. Head and mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Fore wing; 8. Hind wing. Scale bars = 0.3 mm for 2, 0.4 mm for 3, 0.45 mm for 4, 0.7 mm for 5, 0.9 mm for 6 and 7, and 1.1 mm for 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Mesopleuron mostly coarsely and densely punctate, with dense whitish setae (
<figureCitation box="[675,749,1863,1888]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1647,1670]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 8. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 2. Antenna; 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Head, dorsal view; 5. Head and mesosoma, dorsal view; 6. Head and mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Fore wing; 8. Hind wing. Scale bars = 0.3 mm for 2, 0.4 mm for 3, 0.45 mm for 4, 0.7 mm for 5, 0.9 mm for 6 and 7, and 1.1 mm for 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Mesopleuron along promesopleural suture longitudinally striate, along mesometapleural suture smooth. Metapleuron and propodeum laterally smooth and shining (
<figureCitation box="[1352,1422,1899,1924]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1647,1670]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 8. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 2. Antenna; 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Head, dorsal view; 5. Head and mesosoma, dorsal view; 6. Head and mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Fore wing; 8. Hind wing. Scale bars = 0.3 mm for 2, 0.4 mm for 3, 0.45 mm for 4, 0.7 mm for 5, 0.9 mm for 6 and 7, and 1.1 mm for 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Propodeum with whitish setae and reticulate rugose on dorsal and posterior surfaces (
<figureCitation box="[1124,1194,1935,1960]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,977,1000]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,956]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,265,956]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 9. Propodeum, dorsal view; 10 – 12. Metasoma: 10. Lateral view; 11. Dorsal view; 12. Ventral view. Scale bars = 0.5 mm for 9, 0.7 mm for 10, 0.8 mm for 11 and 12." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803826/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); with sparse whitish setae, and shining, transverse shallow depression on lateral surfaces (
<figureCitation box="[925,993,1971,1996]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1647,1670]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 8. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 2. Antenna; 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Head, dorsal view; 5. Head and mesosoma, dorsal view; 6. Head and mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Fore wing; 8. Hind wing. Scale bars = 0.3 mm for 2, 0.4 mm for 3, 0.45 mm for 4, 0.7 mm for 5, 0.9 mm for 6 and 7, and 1.1 mm for 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,289]" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">
<emphasis box="[199,259,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">Legs.</emphasis>
Whitish setae denser on tibiae and tarsi than that on femora. Mid- and hind tibia without preapical dorsal or lateral spines. Fore, mid- and hind tibia with strong tibial spurs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,289]" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">
<emphasis box="[199,274,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">Wings.</emphasis>
Forewing with elongate sclerotized pterostigma; first and second submarginal and first medial cells closed, vein 
<emphasis box="[292,320,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">Rs</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[319,327,275,289]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">2</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[341,395,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">3r-m</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[450,520,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">2m-cu</emphasis>
nebulous; first submarginal cell 0.85 × as long as marginal cell (
<figureCitation box="[1245,1313,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1647,1670]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,340,1627]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 8. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 2. Antenna; 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Head, dorsal view; 5. Head and mesosoma, dorsal view; 6. Head and mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Fore wing; 8. Hind wing. Scale bars = 0.3 mm for 2, 0.4 mm for 3, 0.45 mm for 4, 0.7 mm for 5, 0.9 mm for 6 and 7, and 1.1 mm for 8." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803824/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803824/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="590" targetBox="[151,1436,340,1627]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1647,1731]" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,316,1647,1670]" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">FIGURES 2–8.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[323,525,1648,1670]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Pherotilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brothersi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[323,525,1648,1670]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">
Pherotilla 
<taxonomicName box="[433,525,1648,1670]" pageId="3" pageNumber="590" rank="species" species="brothersi" status="sp. nov.">brothersi</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[533,615,1648,1669]" pageId="3" pageNumber="590" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[533,615,1648,1669]" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, ♂, holotype. 2. Antenna; 3. Head, frontal view; 4. Head, dorsal view; 5. Head and mesosoma, dorsal view; 6. Head and mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Fore wing; 8. Hind wing. Scale bars = 0.3 mm for 2, 0.4 mm for 3, 0.45 mm for 4, 0.7 mm for 5, 0.9 mm for 6 and 7, and 1.1 mm for 8.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1776,2017]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="591" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">
<emphasis box="[199,323,1777,1800]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">Metasoma.</emphasis>
Metasomal segment 1 densely and coarsely punctate, other segments moderately punctate, each segment fringed apically with longer and denser, whitish setae (
<figureCitation box="[873,1005,1812,1837]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,977,1000]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,956]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,265,956]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 9. Propodeum, dorsal view; 10 – 12. Metasoma: 10. Lateral view; 11. Dorsal view; 12. Ventral view. Scale bars = 0.5 mm for 9, 0.7 mm for 10, 0.8 mm for 11 and 12." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803826/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">Figs 10–12</figureCitation>
). Metasomal segment 1 three-quarters as long as hind femur; with two short basal longitudinal lateral carinae on each side of tergum 1; sternum roof like without carina. Metasomal sternum 6 with posterior margin deeply notched on each side and with prominent pair sublateral processes on each side. Pygidium (tergum 7) with median, subgibbose, smooth longitudinal area ending before apex on area length, with apical margin rounded, preapical area smooth, other part of tergum with small punctures mixed with twice larger but sparser ones (
<figureCitation box="[753,838,1992,2017]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1514,1537]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,195,1486]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,195,1493]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 19. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 13. Metasomal tergum 7, dorsal view; 14 – 16. Hypopygium: 14. Ventral view, anterior to left; 15. Lateral view, anterior to left; 16. Posterior view; 17 – 19. Genitalia: 17. Dorsal view; 18. Lateral view; 19. Ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803828/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="590">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Hypopygium (sternum 8) strongly sculptured with lateral peg-like process and broadly and unevenly emarginate posteriorly; lateral process with four strong setae mixed with shorter ones; median emargination with pair strong setae on each side (
<figureCitation box="[1080,1211,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1514,1537]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,195,1486]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,195,1493]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 19. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 13. Metasomal tergum 7, dorsal view; 14 – 16. Hypopygium: 14. Ventral view, anterior to left; 15. Lateral view, anterior to left; 16. Posterior view; 17 – 19. Genitalia: 17. Dorsal view; 18. Lateral view; 19. Ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803828/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Figs 14–16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803826/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="591" targetBox="[151,1436,265,956]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,977,1030]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,328,977,1000]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">FIGURES 9–12.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[335,536,978,1000]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Pherotilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brothersi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[335,536,978,1000]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Pherotilla brothersi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[544,625,978,999]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[544,625,978,999]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, ♂, holotype. 9. Propodeum, dorsal view; 10–12. Metasoma: 10. Lateral view; 11. Dorsal view; 12. Ventral view. Scale bars = 0.5 mm for 9, 0.7 mm for 10, 0.8 mm for 11 and 12.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1075,1460]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis box="[199,312,1075,1100]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Genitalia.</emphasis>
Basal ring moderate. Paramere with narrow apex slightly upcurved; with long dense thin setae, without few slightly thicker long setae near base. Penis valves asymmetrical, right valve longer than left, without setae (
<figureCitation box="[222,353,1147,1172]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1514,1537]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,195,1486]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,195,1493]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 19. Pherotilla brothersi sp. nov., ♂, holotype. 13. Metasomal tergum 7, dorsal view; 14 – 16. Hypopygium: 14. Ventral view, anterior to left; 15. Lateral view, anterior to left; 16. Posterior view; 17 – 19. Genitalia: 17. Dorsal view; 18. Lateral view; 19. Ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803828/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Figs 17–19</figureCitation>
). Volsella somewhat swollen with microsetae dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1075,1460]" box="[199,414,1183,1208]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Female. Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,545,1219,1244]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1075,1460]" box="[199,545,1219,1244]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1219,1244]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,426,1219,1244]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[441,533,1219,1243]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="591" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1075,1460]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1255,1280]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Remarks.</emphasis>
The male of 
<taxonomicName box="[461,589,1255,1280]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Pherotilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brothersi">
<emphasis box="[461,589,1255,1280]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">P. brothersi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to that of 
<emphasis box="[812,940,1256,1279]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">P. oceanica</emphasis>
, but differs in having body entirely black (at least antenna, mandible, tegula and legs partly reddish-brown in 
<emphasis box="[905,1037,1292,1315]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">P. oceanica</emphasis>
); paramere with dense long setae, without longer thicker setae along basodorsal margin (with dense short setae, and one longer thicker setae along basodorsal margin in 
<emphasis box="[392,521,1364,1387]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">P. oceanica</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="591" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1075,1460]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1399,1424]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is dedicated to Denis J. Brothers, the world authority in 
<taxonomicName box="[1160,1280,1399,1424]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mutillidae</taxonomicName>
, who recently revised the subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[399,611,1435,1460]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Rhopalomutillinae">Rhopalomutillinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
